ADDITIONAL AGREEMENT to the Agreement on Watchmaking between the European Economic Community and its Member States and the Swiss Confederation
THE COUNCIL OF EUROPEAN COMMUNITY

THE SWITZERLAND COUNCIL

RECALLING that an Agreement on watchmaking was signed in Geneva on 30 June 1967 between the European Economic Community and its Member States and the Swiss Confederation ,
CONSIDERING the need to take additional measures to ensure the proper functioning of this Agreement ,
RECALLING the Ordinance of the Swiss Federal Council of 23 December 1971 on the use of the Swiss name for watches ,
CONSIDERING the close industrial cooperation between the European Economic Community and Switzerland in the field of the watch industry ,
NOTING that the rationalisation premiums granted by Ebauches SA and ASUAG will be abolished on the date of entry into force of this Agreement and that at the same time the quota referred to in paragraph B 3 ( b ) of the abovementioned Agreement will be abolished ;
1 . The Convention shall be drawn up in French only .
HOW TO CONVENT :

The tariff reductions provided for in Articles 1 and 5 of the Agreement of 30 June 1967 shall enter into force simultaneously with that Agreement .

In order for a watch whose movement contains at least 50 % of the value of all components , including the cost of assembly , of Swiss manufacture to be considered a Swiss watch , a confirmation procedure shall be established between Switzerland and the Community pursuant to Article 2 ( 2 ) ( b ) of the Swiss Federal Council Regulation of 23 December 1971 on the use of the Swiss name for watches , in accordance with the following rules :
1 . Raw movements manufactured in the Community and included in the list annexed to the Agreement , as well as regulatory components and other components of the movement manufactured in the Community supplementing raw movements manufactured in Switzerland or in the Community , shall be deemed to be of equivalent quality to raw movements and components manufactured in Switzerland with comparable technical characteristics .
Watches and movements composed of these raw movements and individual parts must comply with the requirements of statutory technical control in Switzerland .
2 . The list of unfinished works manufactured in the Community as provided for in paragraph 1 shall be regularly revised in accordance with the following procedures :
( a ) The application for inclusion in the list of new raw movement calibres shall be addressed to the Swiss Chamber of Watches by the associations of the Community watchmaking industry or by manufacturers of raw movements established in the Community , accompanied by a technical description of the raw movement calibres .
The Swiss Clock Chamber enters the new caliber ( s ) in the above list without delay .
If an application is made for inclusion in the list for a raw movement calibre that has already been used in Switzerland and has not passed the legal technical inspection in Switzerland , the Swiss Clock Chamber may refuse inclusion .
In this case , the applicant may avail himself of the procedure referred to in paragraph 3 .
b ) The withdrawal of raw movement calibres from the list shall be notified to the Swiss Chamber of Watches by the Community watchmaking industry associations or by the manufacturer who has previously applied for inclusion .
c ) If the requirements of statutory technical control in Switzerland are not met , the Swiss Clock Chamber may request the removal of the calibres concerned from the list ; it shall inform the party concerned accordingly .
If it does not agree , it may invoke the procedure referred to in paragraph 3 within two months .
( d ) Any request to amend the list in accordance with paragraphs ( a ) , ( b ) and ( c ) shall be immediately notified to the Mixed Committee by the Swiss Clock Chamber .
3 . If the equivalence of quality is contested , the matter shall be referred to the Joint Commission provided for in Article 9 of the Agreement of 30 June 1967 by the parties concerned without delay .
The first acting party shall request a joint opinion of its own accord from the Institute for Official Quality Control in the Swiss Watch Industry and from a corresponding qualified Community institute designated by the Community party concerned .
The institutes have three months in which to prepare the required expert opinion .
In view of this opinion , the institutes agree to take from a Swiss undertaking and from a Community undertaking a batch of watches or movements which is sufficiently representative and does not , in principle , comprise more than 50 watches or movements .
After checking these lots in accordance with the Swiss statutory technical control standards , the institutes compare their results and draw up a joint report for the Joint Commission with its conclusions and possible proposals .
The Joint Commission will consider this report at its next meeting .

The Agreement and the list annexed to it shall be published in the official publication bodies of the Contracting Parties and notified to watch manufacturers by the professional associations concerned .
Changes to the attached list will be published and communicated in the same way .
At least every three years from the entry into force of the Agreement , the Joint Commission will revise the list to take account of the registrations and deletions that have taken place .
The new list will be published and communicated in the same way .
All further information can be obtained from the professional associations concerned .

The agreement may be terminated by any Contracting Party with a period of 12 months .
Article 5
The Agreement shall be concluded and ratified by the Contracting Parties in accordance with their respective constitutional provisions .
The Agreement will enter into force on 1 January 1973 , provided that instruments of ratification have been exchanged by that date .
If the exchange of instruments of ratification takes place between 1 January and 30 November 1973 , the Agreement shall enter into force on the first day of the second month following the exchange .


