Amendment of the Agreement between the European Atomic Energy Community ( Euratom ) and the Government of Canada of 6 October 1959 ( 1 ) on Cooperation in the Peaceful Uses of Atomic Energy in the form of an Exchange of Letters ( 78 / 217 / Euratom )
( 1 ) OJ No .
Nr. 60 of 24.11.1959 , pp. 1165 / 59 . COMMISSION OF THE EUROPEAN COMMUNITIES
between the Kingdom of Belgium , the Kingdom of Denmark , the Federal Republic of Germany , Ireland , the Italian Republic , the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg , the Kingdom of the Netherlands , the European Atomic Energy Community and the International Atomic Energy Agency pursuant to Article III ( 1 ) and ( 4 ) of the Treaty on the Non @-@ Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons ( 78 / 164 / Euratom )
CONSIDERING that the Kingdom of Belgium , the Kingdom of Denmark , the Federal Republic of Germany , Ireland , the Italian Republic , the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg and the Kingdom of the Netherlands - hereinafter referred to as &quot; the States &quot; - are signatories to the Treaty on the Non @-@ Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons ( hereinafter referred to as &quot; the Treaty &quot; ) , opened for signature in London , Moscow and Washington on 1 July 1968 and which entered into force on 5 March 1970 ;
RECALLING that Article IV ( 1 ) of the Treaty should not be interpreted as affecting the inalienable right of all Parties to develop research , production and use of nuclear energy for peaceful purposes , while respecting equal treatment in accordance with Articles I and II of the Treaty ;
RECALLING that , pursuant to Article IV ( 2 ) of the Treaty , all Parties undertake to facilitate the widest possible exchange of equipment , material and scientific and technological information for the peaceful use of nuclear energy and are entitled to participate ;
RECALLING that , in accordance with the same paragraph , the Parties which are in a position to do so shall also cooperate to contribute , alone or jointly with other States or international organisations , to the further development of the use of nuclear energy for peaceful purposes , particularly in the territory of non @-@ nuclear weapon States which are Parties ;
CONSIDERING that Article III ( 1 ) of the Treaty obliges any non @-@ nuclear weapons State Party to adopt safeguards as laid down in an agreement to be negotiated and excluded from the International Atomic Energy Agency ( hereinafter referred to as &quot; the Organisation &quot; ) , in accordance with its Statute ( hereinafter referred to as &quot; the Statute &quot; ) , and its safeguard system , with the sole purpose of verifying compliance with its obligations under this Treaty in order to prevent nuclear energy from being diverted from peaceful use and used for nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices ;
CONSIDERING that Article III , paragraph 4 , provides that Non @-@ Nuclear Weapons States Parties , either individually or jointly with other States , shall conclude agreements with them in accordance with the Statute in order to meet the requirements of this Article ;
CONSIDERING that the States are members of the European Atomic Energy Community ( Euratom ) - hereinafter referred to as &quot; the Community &quot; - and that common institutions of the European Communities have conferred upon them legislative , executive and judicial powers which they exercise independently in the areas within their competence and which may take direct effect within the legal systems of the Member States ;
CONSIDERING that , within this institutional framework , the Community has a particular role to ensure , through appropriate safeguards , that nuclear material is not diverted for purposes for which it was not intended and that , from the date of entry into force of the Treaty in the territories of States , it will therefore be up to the Community , by means of safeguards established by the Euratom Treaty , to ensure that no source or special fissile material for nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices is diverted in the territories of States for all peaceful nuclear activities ;
CONSIDERING that these safeguards include in particular the communication to the Community of the basic technical characteristics of nuclear installations , the keeping and submission of operational protocols enabling nuclear material accounting for the Community as a whole , inspections by Community officials and a system of sanctions ;
CONSIDERING that it is the duty of the Community to establish links with other countries and with international organisations suitable to promote progress in the use of nuclear energy for peaceful purposes and that it is expressly authorised to exercise special safeguards obligations in an agreement with a third State or an international organisation ;
CONSIDERING that the international safeguard system of the Organisation referred to in the Treaty includes , in particular , provisions on the submission of investment data to the Organisation , the keeping of minutes , the submission of reports on all nuclear material subject to the safeguards measures of the Organisation , inspections by inspectors of the Organisation , requirements for the establishment and maintenance by a State of an accounting and control system for nuclear material , and measures for verification of non @-@ diversion of such material ;
CONSIDERING that , in the light of the tasks assigned to it by the Statute and its relationship with the General Assembly and the United Nations Security Council , the Organisation must ensure responsibly to the international community that effective safeguards under the Treaty are applied ;
NOTING that States which were Members of the Community at the time of signature of the Treaty made it known on that occasion that the safeguards provided for in Article III , paragraph 1 , of the Treaty would have to be laid down in a verification agreement between the Community , the States and the Organisation and defined in such a way as not to affect the rights and obligations of States and the Community ;
CONSIDERING that the Board of Governors of the Organisation , hereinafter referred to as &quot; the Council , &quot; has approved comprehensive model provisions on the structure and content of the arrangements between the Organisation and States required under the Treaty to be used as a basis for the negotiation of arrangements for safeguards between the Organisation and non @-@ nuclear weapon States party to the Treaty ;
CONSIDERING that Article III A 5 of the Statute empowers the Organisation to apply safeguards , if requested by the parties concerned , to bilateral or multilateral agreements or , if requested by a State , to its activities in the field of nuclear energy ;
CONSIDERING that it is the wish of the Organisation , the Community and States to avoid unnecessary duplication of efforts in the field of safeguards ,
ARE THE ORGANIZATION , THE COMMUNITY AND THE STATES AGREEMENT AS :
PART I
BASIC COMMITMENT

In accordance with Article III ( 1 ) of the Treaty , States undertake to adopt safeguards , in accordance with this Convention , for all source and special fissile material in all peaceful nuclear activities carried out on their territory , under their jurisdiction or under their control in any place , with the sole purpose of verifying that such material is not diverted for nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices .
APPLICATION OF SAFETY MEASURES

The Organization shall have the right and obligation to ensure that safeguards in accordance with this Convention apply to all source and special fissile material in all peaceful nuclear activities carried out in the territories of States , under their jurisdiction or under their control in any place , with the sole purpose of verifying that such material is not diverted for nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices .

( a ) The Community undertakes to cooperate with the Organisation , in accordance with this Convention , in applying its safeguards to source and special fissile material in all peaceful nuclear activities in the territories of States , in order to ensure that such source and special fissile material is not diverted for nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices .
( b ) The Organisation shall apply its safeguards in accordance with this Convention in such a way as to enable it to verify the findings of the Community safeguards system by ensuring that no nuclear material has been diverted from peaceful use and used for nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices .
Inspection by the Organisation shall include , inter alia , independent measurements and observations by the Organisation in accordance with the procedures laid down in this Convention .
In its inspection , the Organisation shall take due account of the effectiveness of the Community &apos;s guarantee system in accordance with this Convention .
COOPERATION BETWEEN ORGANIZATION , COMMUNITY AND STATES

The Organisation , the Community and States shall cooperate as far as each Contracting Party is concerned to facilitate the implementation of the safeguards provided for in this Convention and shall avoid unnecessary duplication of efforts in the field of safeguards .
IMPLEMENTATION OF SECURITY MEASURES
Article 5
The safeguards provided for in this Convention shall be implemented in such a way as not to ( a ) impede economic and technological development in the Community or international cooperation in the field of peaceful nuclear activities , including the international exchange of nuclear material ;
( b ) do not constitute an undue interference with peaceful nuclear activities in the Community , in particular the operation of installations ;
( c ) be consistent with the prudent management practices necessary for the economic and safe conduct of nuclear activities .

( a ) The Organization shall take all precautions to protect trade and industrial secrets and other confidential information of which it becomes aware in the implementation of this Convention .
( b ) ( i ) The Organisation shall not make public any information which it has received in connection with the implementation of this Convention , nor shall it communicate it to a State , organisation or person , except for certain information relating to the implementation of the Convention which may be provided to the Council and to such employees of the Organisation who must be made aware of it in order to fulfil their official functions relating to safeguards , but only to the extent necessary for the performance of the tasks of the Organisation in the implementation of this Convention .
( ii ) Condensed information on nuclear material subject to safeguards under this Convention may be made public by decision of the Council and with the consent of the States or the Community directly concerned , insofar as each of the two Parties is concerned .

( a ) The implementation of safeguards under this Convention shall take full account of technological developments in the field of safeguards and shall make every effort to ensure optimum cost @-@ effectiveness and the application of the principle of effective safeguards for the flow of nuclear material subject to safeguards under this Convention , through the use of instruments and other technical procedures at specific strategic points , where present or future technology permits .
( b ) To ensure optimum cost @-@ effectiveness , the following procedures will be used , for example : ( i ) spatial demarcation as a means of defining material balance zones for accounting purposes ;
( ii ) Statistical methods and sampling for assessing the flow of nuclear material ;
( iii ) Concentrate verification procedures on the fuel cycle stages relating to the manufacture , processing , use and storage of nuclear material from which nuclear weapons and other nuclear explosive devices could easily be manufactured , and limit as far as possible verification procedures for other nuclear material , provided that this does not impede the implementation of this Convention .
DISTRIBUTION OF INFORMATION TO THE ORGANIZATION
Article 8
( a ) In order to effectively implement the safeguards provided for in this Convention , the Community shall provide the Organisation , in accordance with this Convention , with information on nuclear material subject to safeguards and on the characteristics of installations relevant to the implementation of safeguards in respect of such material .
( b ) ( i ) The Organization shall require only the minimum amount of information and data compatible with the performance of its tasks under this Convention .
( ii ) Information on installations shall be limited to the minimum necessary for the application of safeguards relating to nuclear material subject to safeguards under this Convention .
( c ) At the request of the Community , the Organisation is prepared to examine investment data which the Community considers to be particularly vulnerable on Community premises .
Such data need not be communicated materially to the Organisation , provided that they remain readily available on the premises of the Community for further verification by the Organisation .
INSPECTORS OF ORGANIZATION

( a ) ( i ) The Organization shall seek the agreement of the Community and States on the designation of inspectors for States .
( ii ) If the Community objects either to a proposed designation or at any time to a designation being made , the Organisation of the Community and the States shall propose one or more alternative designations .
( iii ) Should the Community &apos;s repeated refusal to agree to the appointment of inspectors of the Organisation impede the inspections to be carried out under this Convention , the Council will discuss the refusal , after having been referred to it by the Director @-@ General of the Organisation - hereinafter referred to as &quot; the Director @-@ General &quot; - with a view to taking appropriate action .
( b ) The Community and the States concerned shall take the necessary steps to ensure that the inspectors of the Organisation can effectively perform the tasks incumbent upon them under their Convention .
( c ) The visits and activities of the inspectors of the Organization shall be organized in such a way as to ( i ) minimize possible nuisance and disturbance to the Community and States and to peaceful nuclear activities subject to the inspection ;
( ii ) Ensure the protection of industrial secrets and other confidential information brought to the attention of the inspectors of the Organisation .
RIGHTS AND LISERATIONS

Each State shall apply to the Organisation , including its assets , resources and assets , as well as to its inspectors and other officials performing tasks under this Convention , the relevant provisions of the Agreement on Privileges and Immunities of the International Atomic Energy Agency .
CONSUMPTION OR Dilution OF CORE MATERIAL
Article 11
The safeguards provided for in this Convention shall be terminated in respect of nuclear material if the Community and the Organisation determine that the material has been consumed or diluted to such an extent that it is no longer usable or practically unrecoverable for a nuclear activity relevant from the point of view of safeguards .
FROM CORE MATERIAL FROM THE STATES
Article 12
In accordance with this Convention , the Community shall notify the Organisation of the transfer of nuclear material from the States subject to the safeguards provided for in this Convention .
The safeguards provided for in this Convention shall be terminated in respect of nuclear material as soon as the recipient State has assumed responsibility , as provided for in this Convention .
The Organization shall keep documentation indicating any transfer and , where applicable , the reapplication of safeguards to the transferred nuclear material .
PROVISIONS RELATED TO CORE MATERIALS THAT ARE USED IN NON @-@ NUCLEAR Activities :
Article 13
Where nuclear material subject to safeguards under this Convention is intended to be used in non @-@ nuclear activities , such as the manufacture of alloys or ceramics , the Community agrees with the Organisation of such uses of the material under which the safeguards under this Convention may be terminated in respect of that material .
NON @-@ APPLICATION OF SAFETY MEASURES ON CORE MATERIALS THAT SHOULD BE USED IN NON @-@ PEACE Activities
Article 14
If a State intends , in its sole discretion , to use nuclear material for which safeguards are required under this Convention , in a nuclear activity which does not require the application of such safeguards , the following procedures shall be followed : ( a ) The Community and the State shall inform the Organisation of the activity and the State shall make it clear ( i ) that the use of the nuclear material in a non @-@ prohibited military activity shall not contravene an obligation entered into by the State with safeguards of the Organisation to use the material only for peaceful nuclear activity ;
( ii ) that the kernel material shall not be used for the manufacture of nuclear weapons and other nuclear warheads during the period of non @-@ application of the safeguards provided for in this Convention .
( b ) The Organisation and the Community shall determine that the safeguards provided for in this Convention shall not be applied only as long as the nuclear material is used in such activity .
The scheme sets out , as far as possible , for how long and under what circumstances these safeguards will not be applied .
In any case , the safeguards provided for in this Convention will be re @-@ applied as soon as the nuclear material is returned to peaceful nuclear activity .
The Organisation shall be kept informed of the total quantity and composition of such material in the State or States concerned and of any transfer of such material from that State or States .
c ) Any such provision shall be made in agreement with the Organization .
The latter declares its consent as soon as possible ; it covers only matters such as , inter alia , the timing and procedures and arrangements for reporting , but does not include approval or knowledge of military activities in secret , nor does it cover the use of nuclear material therein .
FINANCE
Article 15
The Organisation , the Community and States shall bear the costs incurred by each of them in implementing their respective obligations under this Convention .
If , however , extraordinary costs arise for the Community , States or persons under its jurisdiction as a result of a specific request by the Organisation , the Organisation shall reimburse such costs , provided that it has agreed to do so in advance .
In any case , the Organisation shall bear the cost of any additional measurements and sampling required by the inspectors of the Organisation .
LIABILITY FOR NUKLEAR DAMAGES
Article 16
The Community and States shall ensure that liability protection for nuclear damage , including insurance or other financial security , which may be claimed in accordance with their laws and regulations , shall apply to the Organisation and its officials for the purposes of implementing this Convention in the same way as to the nationals of States .
INTERNATIONAL RELIABILITY
Article 17
Any claim by the Community or a State against the Organisation or the Organisation against the Community or a State for damage other than damage arising from a nuclear incident arising from the implementation of the safeguards provided for in this Convention shall be governed in accordance with international law .
MEASURES RELATED TO THE REVIEW OF NON @-@ DEPARTMENT
Article 18
If , on the basis of a report from the Director @-@ General , the Council decides that a Community or State action , as far as each of the two Parties is concerned , is essential and urgent in order to verify that nuclear material subject to safeguards under this Convention is not diverted for nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices , the Council may request the Community or the State to take the necessary measure without delay , irrespective of whether a dispute settlement procedure under Article 22 has been initiated .
Article 19
If , after examining the relevant information provided to it by the Director @-@ General , the Council determines that the Organisation is not in a position to verify by verification that no nuclear material subject to safeguards under this Convention has been diverted for nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices , it may submit the reports provided for in Article XII , paragraph C of the Statute and , where appropriate , take the other measures provided for therein .
In taking such steps , the Council shall take into account the degree of certainty obtained by the safeguards applied and shall provide the Community or the State - as far as each of the two Parties is concerned - with every reasonable opportunity to provide the Council with the necessary assurance .
SETTING AND APPLICATION OF THE CONVENTION AND PARTICIPATION OF POSSIBILITIES
Article 20
Consultations shall be held at the request of the Organisation , the Community or any State on matters arising out of the interpretation or application of this Convention .
Article 21
The Community and the States are entitled to request that questions arising from the interpretation or application of this Convention be examined by the Council .
The Council invites the Community and the State concerned to participate in the discussion of such issues by the Council .
Article 22
With the exception of disputes arising out of the interpretation or application of this Convention and not settled by negotiation or by any other procedure agreed by the Organisation , the Community and the States , disputes arising out of a decision of the Council pursuant to Article 19 or a measure taken by the Council shall be referred , at the request of a party , to an arbitral tribunal composed of five arbitrators .
The Community and the States shall appoint two arbitrators , the Organisation shall also appoint two arbitrators and the four arbitrators designated in this way shall appoint a fifth arbitrator to preside .
If the Community and States or the Organisation do not designate two arbitrators each within thirty days of the request for an arbitral award , the Community or the Organisation may request the President of the International Court of Justice to appoint such arbitrators .
The same procedure shall apply if the fifth arbitrator has not yet been elected within thirty days of the appointment or appointment of the fourth arbitrator .
A majority of the members of the arbitral tribunal have a quorum and all decisions require the consent of at least three arbitrators .
The arbitration procedure shall be determined by the arbitral tribunal .
The decisions of the arbitral tribunal shall be binding on the Organisation , the Community and the States concerned .

Article 23
( a ) This Convention shall enter into force for non @-@ nuclear weapon States party to the Treaty and becoming members of the Community ; ( i ) if the State concerned notifies the Organisation that its procedures for the entry into force of this Convention have been completed ; and
( ii ) when the Community notifies the Organisation that it is in a position to apply its safeguards in respect of that State for the purposes of this Convention .
( b ) If the State concerned has concluded other agreements with the Organisation on the application of the safeguards of the Organisation , the application of safeguards of the Organisation by virtue of such agreements shall be suspended for the State as long as this Convention is in force on entry into force , provided , however , that the obligation of the State undertaken in such an agreement not to use items covered by such agreements in a manner conducive to military purposes remains valid .
CHANGE OF THE CONVENTION

( a ) The Organisation , the Community and States shall consult each other on an amendment of this Convention at the request of one of the Contracting Parties .
( b ) All amendments shall require the agreement of the Organization , the Community and States .
( c ) The Director @-@ General shall immediately inform all Member States of the Organisation of any amendment to this Convention .
INFORMATION AND APPLICATION DURATION

( a ) This Convention shall enter into force on the date on which the Organisation receives written notification from the Community and the States that their procedures for entry into force have been completed .
The Director @-@ General shall immediately inform all Member States of the Organisation of the entry into force of this Convention .
b ) This Convention shall remain in force as long as the States Parties to the Treaty are parties to it .

Article 26
The Protocol annexed to this Convention is an integral part of the Convention .
The term &quot; Convention &quot; used in this Convention means the Convention and the Protocol together .
PART II
INTRODUCT

The purpose of this Part of the Convention is to define , as necessary , the procedures to be followed in the implementation of the provisions of Part I on safeguards .
DESTINATION OF SECURITY MEASURES

The safeguards established in this Convention aim at the timely detection of the diversion of significant quantities of nuclear material from peaceful nuclear activities for the production of nuclear weapons and other nuclear warheads for unknown purposes and at deterring such diversion through the risk of early detection .
Article 29
In order to achieve the objective set out in Article 28 , material accounting is used as a security measure of fundamental importance , combined with spatial limitation and observation as important complementary measures .
Article 30
The technical completion of the inspections by the Organisation shall be effected by means of a declaration listing for each material balance zone the quantity of material not detected for a certain period of time and specifying the accuracy limits for the indicated megacities .
COMMUNITY SECURITY SYSTEM
Article 31
In carrying out its inspections , the Organisation shall make full use of the Community guarantee system in accordance with Article 3 .
Article 32
The Community accounting and control system for nuclear material in accordance with this Convention is grouped into material balance zones .
In applying its safeguard measures , the Community will make use of the procedures and measures of the following nature and , where necessary , provide for them as specified and appropriate in the Supplementary Agreements :
( a ) A measurement system for determining the quantities of nuclear material received , manufactured , shipped , lost or otherwise removed from the stock and the quantities of the stock ;
b ) the evaluation of the reproducibility and accuracy of the measurements and the estimation of the measurement uncertainty ;
( c ) Procedures for identifying , verifying and evaluating differences in measurements between sender and recipient ;
( d ) procedures for recording the actual stock ;
( e ) procedures for assessing accumulations of unmeasured stocks and unmeasured losses ;
( f ) A protocol and reporting system identifying the nuclear inventory and changes in that inventory for each material balance zone , including the inputs and outputs of the material balance zone ;
( g ) arrangements to ensure that accounting procedures and arrangements are correctly implemented ;
( h ) Procedures for reporting to the Organisation in accordance with Articles 59 to 65 and 67 to 69 .
Article 33
The safeguards provided for in this Convention do not extend to material used in mining or in ore processing .
Article 34
( a ) If material containing uranium or thorium which has not yet reached the stage of the nuclear fuel cycle described in paragraph ( c ) above is exported , directly or indirectly , to a non @-@ nuclear weapons State party to this Convention , the Community shall inform the Organisation of the quantity , composition and destination of such material , unless it is exported for specific non @-@ nuclear purposes ;
( b ) if material containing uranium or thorium which has not yet reached the stage of the nuclear fuel cycle described in paragraph ( c ) above is imported into the States , the Community shall inform the Organisation of the quantity and composition of the material , unless it is imported for specific non @-@ nuclear purposes ;
( c ) If nuclear material suitable for fuel production or isotope enrichment in terms of composition and purity leaves the plant or process phase in which it is produced , or if such nuclear material or other nuclear material produced at a later stage of the nuclear fuel cycle is imported into the States , it shall be subject to the other safeguards referred to in this Convention .
FINISHING THE SECURITY MEASURES
Article 35
( a ) The safeguards provided for in this Convention shall be terminated for nuclear material under the conditions set out in Article 11 . However , if the conditions set out in Article 11 are not fulfilled , the Community considers that recovery from residues of nuclear material subject to safeguards under this Convention is provisionally not possible or desirable , the Organisation and the Community shall consult each other on the application of appropriate safeguards .
( b ) The safeguards provided for in this Convention shall be terminated for nuclear material under the conditions set out in Article 13 , provided that the Organisation and the Community agree that such nuclear material is practically unrecoverable .
LIMITATION OF THE SECURITY MEASURES
Article 36
At the request of the Community , the Organisation shall exempt the following nuclear material from the safeguards provided for in this Convention :
a ) special fissile material when used in grams or smaller quantities as a sensor in instruments ;
( b ) nuclear material when used in non @-@ nuclear activities referred to in Article 13 , if such nuclear material is recoverable ; and
( c ) Plutonium with an isotope concentration of plutonium -238 exceeding 80 % .
Article 37
At the request of the Community , the Organisation shall exempt from such safeguards nuclear material which would otherwise be subject to safeguards under this Convention , provided that the total quantity of nuclear material exempted in the States pursuant to this Article does not at any time exceed :
a ) a total of one kilogram of special palatable material which may consist of one or more of the following materials :
( i ) plutonium ;
( ii ) Uranium with enrichment of 0.2 ( 20 % ) and above , calculated by multiplying its weight by enrichment ;
( iii ) Uranium with enrichment below 0.2 ( 20 % ) and above that of natural uranium , calculated by multiplying its weight by five times the square of enrichment ;
( b ) a total of ten metric tonnes of natural uranium and depleted uranium with enrichment exceeding 0.005 ( 0.5 % ) ;
( c ) twenty metric tonnes of depleted uranium with enrichment of 0.005 ( 0.5 % ) or less ;
d ) Twenty metric tons of thorium
or larger quantities which can be fixed by the Council for uniform application .
Article 38
If liberated nuclear material is to be processed or stored together with nuclear material subject to the safeguards provided for in this Convention , arrangements shall be made for the re @-@ application of safeguards to that material .
SUPPLEMENTARY FACILITIES
Article 39
