A. Letter from the Bank for International Settlements
Mr President .
The BIS could enter into standby credit agreements with the central banks of creditor countries if the banks so request .
The agreements could be concluded up to the total amount of the contribution paid by the creditor country to the mechanism , within a total limit of 2.725 billion units of account , representing 50 % of all future deployment funds of the member states .
The details of the standby agreements would have to be settled between the BIS and the relevant central bank .
However , a number of conditions that the MIS would be willing to apply are already listed below .
For each standby loan , the BIS would initially undertake a two @-@ year commitment , with the possibility of extending it , but not exceeding five years in total .
The BIS would charge a credit opening commission on the opening of the loans and on any renewal thereof .
Furthermore , it would be agreed that the first drawings would not be made before the end of one month after the standby agreement in order to allow the Bank to make the necessary adjustments to its own liquidity .
The drawings would be made in the currencies available to the BIS upon conclusion of the agreement , most likely in US dollars ; they would cover periods to be negotiated taking into account the Bank &apos;s resources , probably three or six months .
The terms would be similar to those applied by the BIS to transactions under similar conditions at any given time , i.e. interest rates would be broadly in line with market rates .
Normally , interest rates would be marginally higher than Libor .
However , if the BIS has to raise the necessary funds on the market itself , the interest rate applied could reach a maximum equivalent to the Libor increased by a corresponding margin .
I would be grateful if you could inform me of the agreement of the Council of the European Communities .
