CONVINCED that greater international cooperation should be implemented in such a way as to contribute to greater liberalisation , stability and expansion of international trade in meat and live animals ;
TAKING NOTE of the need to avoid serious disruption of international trade in beef and live bovine animals ;
RECOGNISING the importance of beef and live bovine production and trade in these products for the economies of many countries , in particular certain developed and developing countries ;
RECALLING their commitments to the principles and objectives of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade - hereinafter referred to as the &quot; General Agreement &quot; or &quot; GATT &quot; ( 1 ) ;
DECIDED , in pursuing the objectives of this Agreement , to implement the principles and objectives agreed in the Tokyo Declaration of Ministers of 14 September 1973 concerning multilateral trade negotiations , in particular with regard to the special and more favourable treatment of developing countries ;
the Participants to this Convention , through their representatives , have agreed as follows :
PART I
GENERAL PROVISIONS

Goals
The objectives of this Agreement are to promote , 1 . , the expansion , further liberalisation and stability of the international meat and livestock market by facilitating the progressive dismantling of barriers and restrictions on world trade in beef and live bovine animals , including the measures affecting the distribution of such trade , and by improving the international framework of world trade to the benefit of consumers and producers , as well as importing and exporting countries ;
Encourage greater international cooperation on all issues relating to trade in beef and live bovine animals , in particular with a view to greater rationalisation and a more effective distribution of resources in the international meat industry ;
3 . Ensure additional benefits for developing countries &apos; external trade in beef and live bovine animals by improving their opportunities to participate in the expansion of world trade in these products , inter alia by : ( a ) promoting long @-@ term price stability in the context of an expanding world market for beef and live bovine animals ; and
( b ) promoting the maintenance and improvement of the proceeds of beef and live cattle exporting developing countries ;
and this in order to generate additional revenues by ensuring the long @-@ term stability of the beef and live cattle markets ;
4 . Further expansion of trade on the basis of competition , taking into account the traditional position of efficient producers .
